description: From Middle English upsenden, equivalent to up- +‎ send. Cognate with Scots upsend (“to ascend”), Dutch opzenden (“to redirect, forward”), Low German upsenden (“to send up, deliver (mail)”), Swedish uppsända (“to offer up”).

entries.meaning: The ability to send up, or transmit.
examples: The Trans-Vista 2000 offers Mosler options like upsend capability, automatic carrier return and fast, accurate customer identification.

verbs.description: upsend (third-person singular simple present upsends, present participle upsending, simple past and past participle upsent)

entries.meaning: (transitive, archaic) To send, cast, or throw up; deliver; submit.
examples: And now upsend afar a deaf'ning shout [...]

entries.meaning: (intransitive, US, Scotland) To ascend; climb up.
examples: But when the sun of the fifth day had risen, The Keepers of the Faith, upon a pyre Built near the council-house, with solemn rites Burnt the White Dog, upsending with the smoke The message of their loyalty and thanks.
